  "runtimeMin": 74,
  "format": "Sean, Amanda, and Chris Ryan spend an hour on Denis Villeneuve's Dune — the spectacle, the mid-movie downshift, the unmarked part-one problem, the box office — then rank Villeneuve's filmography and fight about where Enemy belongs.",
  "segments": [
    {
      "kind": "discussion",
      "heading": "Dune",
      "note": "Sean and Amanda with Chris Ryan",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "Dune",
          "year": 2021,
          "note": "The main text. Amanda's mind was blown for the first hour, then wandered; all three agree the last 45 minutes downshift into a mother-son picnic. Chris's read: it doesn't insult the audience. Debated at length — Zimmer's percussive-choral score, Greg Fraser's photography, the ornithopters and sandworms, the gun-free hand-to-hand combat, the fact that the theatrical print didn't label itself 'Part One,' and the near-certain sequel. $40M domestic, north of $220M worldwide, likely a lock for the below-the-line Oscars."
        },
        {
          "title": "Dune",
          "year": 1984,
          "note": "David Lynch's version, which Sean and Amanda rewatched — compresses two books into 2h15m, a mistake Lynch essentially disowned; its 1984 sandworms hold up better than expected."
        },
        {
          "title": "Jodorowsky's Dune",
          "year": 2013,
          "note": "The documentary on Alejandro Jodorowsky's unmade 1970s adaptation; Sean floats Jodorowsky as the filmmaker better suited to the book's 'space acid' register that Villeneuve avoids."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "kind": "ranking",
      "heading": "The Villeneuve Rankings",
      "note": "the brokered top seven",
      "subject": "Denis Villeneuve",
      "ranked": true,
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "Sicario",
          "year": 2015,
          "note": "No. 1 — where Sean and Chris meet; Sean holds it as the best. 'Sicario means hitman.'"
        },
        {
          "title": "Arrival",
          "year": 2016,
          "note": "No. 2 and Amanda's No. 1; the hopeful one, the movie she's championed on the show for years."
        },
        {
          "title": "Dune",
          "year": 2021,
          "note": "No. 3, everyone 'high off the spice.' Chris slotted it here fresh out of the theater."
        },
        {
          "title": "Blade Runner 2049",
          "year": 2017,
          "note": "No. 4; Chris thinks it gets mired in its own navel-gazing, Amanda rates it above Prisoners."
        },
        {
          "title": "Prisoners",
          "year": 2013,
          "note": "No. 5, the compromise slot. Shot by Deakins, which the group agrees is the only thing keeping it from being 'banned from society.'"
        },
        {
          "title": "Incendies",
          "year": 2010,
          "note": "No. 6; his English-language-adjacent breakthrough for American audiences, adapted from a play, with a traumatic ending."
        },
        {
          "title": "Enemy",
          "year": 2013,
          "note": "No. 7 — 'just shameful,' per Sean, who wanted it at No. 3. Opens on the title card 'chaos is order yet undeciphered.'"
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
